ex:evidence_1066359032686122566 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "biomechanics" ;
    ex:confidence "0.449"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Furthermore, since they don’t allow (or at least encourage) the same degree of horizontal forces, this will help us see how the lift can still be challenging for your triceps while the bar is imposing an elbow extensor moment, and it’ll also help us understand why you can bench more than you can dumbbell bench (it’s not just a matter of stability)." .

ex:evidence_1134823635820424005 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.539"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "In the bench press, the bar applies a downward force that exerts an external flexor moment at your elbow, and external extensor and horizontal extensor moments at your shoulder. -" .

ex:evidence_1167009920365686215 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.576"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "The trickier part: Whether the bar imposes a flexor or extensor moment at the elbow depends on your grip width." .

ex:evidence_1199480061286041807 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.592"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "nasm_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "When performing a bench press with a retracted scapula, some argue the pectoralis muscles enter the stretch reflex position sooner during the eccentric phase." .

ex:evidence_1308227252238123262 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.452"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "frontiersin_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Then, the lifter performed the same testing routine as they did with the first grip width." .

ex:evidence_1382159800585571640 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.539"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "muscleandmotion_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Pectoralis major – primary shoulder horizontal adduction - Anterior deltoid – assists in shoulder horizontal adduction - Coracobrachialis – assists in shoulder horizontal adduction - Triceps brachii – elbow extension - Serratus anterior – scapula protraction - Abdominal muscles – stabilize the torso How to bench press properly: step-by-step - Lie with your back on a flat bench and hold a barbell in your hands." .

ex:evidence_1570690922683155360 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.389"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "robertson_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Another bonus of hitting the mid-back is that increases in size will also shave some inches off your bench press stroke!" .

ex:evidence_1601132158862956336 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "biomechanics" ;
    ex:confidence "0.524"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "mdpi_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "In the current work, after characterising the technical movement, it has been demonstrated that the concentric phase does not encompass the entire lifting motion (rise of the barbell)." .

ex:evidence_1611917198715303091 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "biomechanics" ;
    ex:confidence "0.497"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Furthermore, passive elements in the muscle – structural proteins and connective tissue – produce increasing amounts of force as a muscle lengthens as well (blue curve)." .

ex:evidence_2026636570897469773 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.438"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Kinematic Factors influencing performance in injury risk in the bench press exercise." .

ex:evidence_209686524576622367 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "biomechanics" ;
    ex:confidence "0.525"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Muscle fibers themselves produce the most force when they’re around resting length, and their capacity to produce force increases or decreases as they lengthen or shorten (red curve below)." .

ex:evidence_2158487280669332939 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.247"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "If your elbows are pointed out, then when your triceps contract, they’re mainly imposing lateral forces on the weight." .

ex:evidence_2195844706560522998 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.42"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "frontiersin_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Therefore, it is speculated that different grip widths may influence the muscle activity of the distal prime movers to a greater extent than the proximal prime movers." .

ex:evidence_2201452169132718745 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.263"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "This should be your default assumption since the shoulder flexion demands peak at the bottom of the lift and then drop off dramatically." .

ex:evidence_224828924278779116 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.534"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "frontiersin_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Hence, the wide and medium grip widths produced similar shoulder and elbow joint moments and moment arm at the first located lowest barbell velocity." .

ex:evidence_2378161567906912300 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.424"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "Nike_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Repeat, then rack the barbell." .

ex:evidence_2613310381930980504 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.061"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Internal moments are calculated the same way external moments are." .

ex:evidence_2821606302126264516 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.405"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "However, based on the available research, it seems like incline still doesn’t challenge your upper pecs quite as much reverse grip benching with a wide grip does." .

ex:evidence_2822910088123661922 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.495"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "frontiersin_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "During the sticking region, all grip widths demonstrated similar horizontal forces, but resultant forces decreased, which suggests that this is a poor biomechanical region despite the grip width that is used in the bench press exercise." .

ex:evidence_2960198839173471140 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.331"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Also, your triceps can help out both your pecs and delts which are in a more stretched and vulnerable position." .

ex:evidence_3003186859142029143 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.439"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "muscleandmotion_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Powerlifters arch their back and lift their chest up in order to reduce the distance the barbell needs to travel from the starting position to the chest, thus allowing them to lift heavier weights. *" .

ex:evidence_3109016614205827874 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.451"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "frontiersin_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Duffey and Challis (2011) therefore suggested that the horizontal forces during bench press result from the muscles' engagement in order to generate vertical force; they did not, however, investigate the effect of a horizontal force component in the sticking region." .

ex:evidence_3123029424603546143 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.407"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "nasm_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Scapular retraction also limits protraction and anterior tilting of scapulae (rounding the shoulders forward) during the exercise (Duffey, 2008)." .

ex:evidence_3124050718936935010 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.416"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Maximal intended velocity training induces greater gains in bench press performance than deliberately slower half-velocity training." .

ex:evidence_3154959924904228887 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.19"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "nasm_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "However, this position may place the shoulder in a vulnerable position (Green, 2007)." .

ex:evidence_3165110941414364996 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.443"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "Nike_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Because the bench press engages so many muscles at once, it can help you build muscle mass and see definition quicker than most upper-body exercises." .

ex:evidence_3246288064624047774 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.278"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Maybe muscle irradiation (when one muscle contracts hard, it’s easier for nearby muscles to contract hard – in this case, your forearm muscles contracting as hard as possible may help your triceps contract harder)." .

ex:evidence_3302011814102862551 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.366"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "mdpi_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Regarding the analysis of the movement pattern in this training exercise, the first study on BP kinematics [24] revealed that the barbell movement followed a very similar pattern across subjects." .

ex:evidence_333877969717209455 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.459"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "nasm_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Start with a standard grip of the bar approximately shoulder-width and the upper arms abducted about 45°, and avoid an excessively wide or narrow grip." .

ex:evidence_3439929949147994484 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.259"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Your scapulae can move four basic ways." .

ex:evidence_3445518235617374950 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "biomechanics" ;
    ex:confidence "0.545"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "nasm_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "In addition, this position may be less aggravating for people with a history of shoulder pain because the eccentric phase requires less shoulder horizontal abduction and places a greater emphasis on sagittal plane shoulder extension." .

ex:evidence_3543176544538772560 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.148"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "A few people actually prefer retraction and elevation." .

ex:evidence_3610508913200507183 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "biomechanics" ;
    ex:confidence "0.422"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "If you weren’t supporting the bar, it would accelerate downward at 9.8m/sec2 (due to gravity), so the bar is exerting 150kg x 9.8m/sec2 = 1470N of force upon your hands and arms." .

ex:evidence_3733145813948963270 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.455"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Bench with a variety of different grips (both width, and pronated/supinated) Pin press from varying heights Board press with various boards DB bench press Bench with a cambered (MacDonald) bar Bench with pauses of varying lengths At the end of the day… Ultimately, technical improvements can help your bench press dramatically (for both strength and longevity)." .

ex:evidence_3765620780293641670 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.527"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "In simple terms, grip width determines horizontal flexion demands; the further the lateral distance between your hand and your shoulder, the longer the horizontal flexion moment arm." .

ex:evidence_4061153391699735386 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "biomechanics" ;
    ex:confidence "0.443"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "There are only two ways to do that: a) increase your skill as a bencher so your current muscle mass can produce more force during the movement and b) add more muscle!" .

ex:evidence_416381080869618196 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.436"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "While tucking enough that your elbows wind up in front of the bar does make the lift harder on your triceps, this technique can also help you drive the bar back up off your chest (as discussed in the previous section) at the start of the press, allowing your triceps to help out your shoulders." .

ex:evidence_4349657849883051066 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.442"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "muscleandmotion_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Not using a full range of motion is often due to a lack of knowledge, but this can easily be corrected by understanding that the bar should touch the chest for maximum muscle engagement." .

ex:evidence_4429955165024491309 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "biomechanics" ;
    ex:confidence "0.433"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Unfortunately, you can’t change muscle attachment points, so the only factor within your control is increasing contractile force." .

ex:evidence_4450542743904215013 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.202"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "However, by the top, it doesn’t feel like your triceps are contributing anything at all to the movement." .

ex:evidence_4491170996028987750 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.27"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "nasm_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Elite powerlifters may perform the lift with excessive lumbar extension (arched low-back), but this position is not advised for the general fitness enthusiast unless properly instructed, and the person has a specific goal to increase 1 repetition maximum performance." .

ex:evidence_4537114846613274388 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "biomechanics" ;
    ex:confidence "0.532"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "frontiersin_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "This means that the total force vector could influence the moments around the elbow from flexion to an extension moment." .

ex:evidence_4542610623091980092 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.257"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "Nike_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Make It Easier Lighten the load by using an empty barbell (meaning don’t add weight plates; a typical women’s barbell is about 35 pounds, while a typical men’s barbell weighs 45 pounds—so it’s still something." .

ex:evidence_4588624231442321546 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.479"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "frontiersin_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "The wide and medium grip widths produced greater horizontal shoulder moments than the narrow grip width during the sticking region." .

ex:evidence_5072008960390877952 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "biomechanics" ;
    ex:confidence "0.537"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "It IS true that this technique effectively negates the vast majority of shoulder flexion demands, but it also increases range of motion and increases your risk of shoulder injury (that much horizontal flexion while in internal rotation is a good recipe for AC joint impingement)." .

ex:evidence_5243182916828393244 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "biomechanics" ;
    ex:confidence "0.518"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "nasm_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "In other words, an individual will have to use a lighter weight because this motion limits activation of the powerful sternoclavicular portion of the pectoralis muscle." .

ex:evidence_5559248915806005868 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.206"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "For now, so we don’t get too bogged down before getting into the really meaty part of this article, let’s just stick with the same answer: Your triceps extend your elbows." .

ex:evidence_5561136452951860813 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "biomechanics" ;
    ex:confidence "0.436"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "robertson_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Force needs a little further explanation: Force = Mass x Acceleration Mass is essentially the weight on the bar, and acceleration is how fast you are moving the bar (remember, this is a generalization, used to prove a point)." .

ex:evidence_5621870825381301946 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.377"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "Nike_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Why You Should Be Doing a Bench Press - You’ll improve overall upper-body strength, making all kinds of pushing exercises, including push-ups, shoulder presses, and moving furniture, feel easier. -" .

ex:evidence_5703754554645354287 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.363"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "robertson_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Hopefully this article has shed some light on what muscles are working while benching, how to train them, and ways to improve your bench press from start to finish." .

ex:evidence_5765739825564459696 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.475"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Will the bench press, alone, maximize chest and triceps development?" .

ex:evidence_5834603139656420674 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.415"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "robertson_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "More weight equals more muscle and strength, and hopefully a bigger bench press." .

ex:evidence_5937817785645682896 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.361"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "The two heads that originate on the humerus only perform elbow extension, while the long head can also aid in shoulder extension." .

ex:evidence_6017974532576192584 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.529"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "nasm_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "This position creates a stable base of support against the bench for the shoulders, decreases anterior forces through the shoulder complex particularly during the eccentric phase, and may improve activation of the pectoralis muscles (Duffey, 2008; Bench Press Analysis)." .

ex:evidence_6030053731486581522 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.414"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "Nike_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Lower the bar, bending your arms with elbows at a 45- to 70-degree angle, until the bar grazes your chest. -" .

ex:evidence_6063660757057130382 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.504"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "frontiersin_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Considering EMG activity during different grip widths along with the horizontal forces around the sticking region could provide more detailed information about how these muscles generate forces in the sticking region during different grip widths, and how to manipulate the sticking region by choosing a grip width that supports individual strength and weaknesses." .

ex:evidence_6134097589065113081 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.261"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "robertson_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "The hand-off should take the bar to an area above the lower pectoral or high abdominal area (see note below!)." .

ex:evidence_6229863947062040777 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.426"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "I don’t think you could ever pinpoint the triceps as a definite weak link at the bottom of the press, but stronger triceps can give aid to the other muscles that are more likely to acutely limit you." .

ex:evidence_6287577683017703207 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.161"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "This article addresses bar path in much greater detail." .

ex:evidence_6578895069661444131 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.408"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "The wider your grip, the greater lateral distance you’ll have between your hand and your shoulder, so the greater the horizontal flexion demands will be (challenging your pecs specifically)." .

ex:evidence_6674998640416669096 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.313"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "However, that doesn’t necessarily mean that your current grip gives you the most potential to be the strongest." .

ex:evidence_6852806800457485941 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.413"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Incline press will train your front delts slightly harder than flat bench will, and maybe your upper pecs as well." .

ex:evidence_700504495811046891 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.446"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Bar path doesn’t affect horizontal flexion demands, but grip width does." .

ex:evidence_7168396556720604696 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.508"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "nasm_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Movement Pattern > Lower the barbell toward your chest, by flexing your elbows while maintaining scapulae retraction." .

ex:evidence_7488479543817287101 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.276"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Here’s how I like to think of it: pecs provide the “strength base” for the movement, while the triceps give you the extra kick you need for heavier weights." .

ex:evidence_7582889969486512755 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.426"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "frontiersin_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "The subjects performed the bench press according to the rules and regulations set by the International Powerlifting Federation, except that the requirement for a full stop on the chest was removed; they were allowed to touch and press, but no bounce of the barbell was allowed." .

ex:evidence_7671194743898064452 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.618"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "muscleandmotion_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Overly narrow barbell grip Gripping the barbell with your hands too close together during the bench press reduces the workload placed on the pectoralis major and increases the amount of work done by the anterior deltoid and triceps muscles." .

ex:evidence_7789563578189575995 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.449"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "frontiersin_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "It is also speculated that the wide and medium grip widths enable more load to be lifted because they produce greater shoulder flexion moments during all events." .

ex:evidence_7814088056592822175 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.424"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "nasm_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Elite athletes or powerlifters may perform the Valsalva maneuver during the bench press." .

ex:evidence_7837385133000221871 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.384"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "When you bench with a wide grip, the bar doesn’t just magically extend your elbows for you." .

ex:evidence_7893602109449940586 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.494"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "frontiersin_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Where the medium and wide grip widths decreased the shoulder extension moments, the narrow grip width increased the shoulder extension moment during the sticking region." .

ex:evidence_7948072394261811819 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.273"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "However, because they allow you to impart lateral forces on the bar, your triceps actually aid your pecs substantially as well." .

ex:evidence_7954618234305313428 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "biomechanics" ;
    ex:confidence "0.514"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "To add another variable into the mix, the internal moment arm (the leverage a muscle has to pull against the bone it moves) of the muscles involved changes with joint angles as well, so not only does contractile force vary, but the ability to translate that contractile force to internal joint moments varies as well." .

ex:evidence_7974039103464086699 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "biomechanics" ;
    ex:confidence "0.525"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "The two factors that determine whether your muscles can produce large enough internal extensor moments to lift a load are the attachment points of the muscles and the force with which they can contract. -" .

ex:evidence_8033513794439758405 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.089"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "First things first, check your wrist position." .

ex:evidence_8125347921255333747 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.475"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "Nike_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "If the range of motion is tricky for you, do a floor press by lying face up on the floor and lowering your arms until your triceps hit the floor." .

ex:evidence_842825312976450203 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.271"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Because of that, the bench probably doesn’t train the long head of your triceps nearly as much as the other two heads." .

ex:evidence_8445146406805085197 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.469"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "However, for other people, it’s much less comfortable than benching with a pronated grip; many people can’t comfortably supinate their forearms well enough, it puts a pretty fair amount of stress on your wrists since you have to reverse grip bench with your wrists cocked back, and it puts a fair amount of stress on your biceps tendons and the other muscles/tendons/ligaments on the front of your shoulder." .

ex:evidence_8501876243065843923 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.466"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "frontiersin_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Furthermore, the wide grip width produced 13.1–15.7% lateral forces, while the medium and narrow grip widths produced 0.4–1.8 and 8.5–10.1% medially directed forces of the vertical force produced during the sticking region, respectively." .

ex:evidence_8599214282458052764 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.193"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Remember, gravity is always pulling the bar straight down." .

ex:evidence_8871427073111399703 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.475"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "nasm_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "It is also important to note that muscle activation varies depending if the muscle is performing an eccentric muscle action or a concentric muscle contraction, as well as the technique selected by the lifter (i.e., wide grip versus narrow grip)." .

ex:evidence_9046631471674000451 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.453"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "Nike_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "The barbell bench press, one of the “big three” in powerlifting, builds serious upper-body strength and, you guessed it, power, thanks to the number of muscle fibers it activates with every rep." .

ex:evidence_9132910182340614207 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.463"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "For these people, the arm they lock out first is generally the weaker arm – the stronger arm supports the load while the weaker arm gets to press the weight out at an angle, instead of straight up." .

ex:evidence_935160721448039193 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "biomechanics" ;
    ex:confidence "0.478"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "There’s a simple explanation: Muscles don’t produce the same amount of force over their entire range of motion." .

