ex:evidence_4046312411843491737 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.371"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "The other two heads only cross the elbow, while the long head also crosses the shoulder to aid in shoulder extension." .

ex:evidence_4176555419481415005 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "biomechanics" ;
    ex:confidence "0.631"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Because of that, the pecs and the triceps can work synergistically at both the elbow and shoulder; the pecs help the triceps extend the elbow, and the triceps help the pecs horizontally flex the shoulder." .

ex:evidence_4536583117174442223 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.113"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Descent Your next order of business is lowering the bar." .

ex:evidence_543640127723997735 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.476"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "frontiersin_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Furthermore, the medial triceps increased muscle activity through the regions for the wide and medium bench press conditions, while the lateral triceps increased muscle activity from the pre-sticking to the post-sticking region." .

ex:evidence_7129468600132720072 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "domain" ;
    ex:confidence "0.136"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "strongerbyscience_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Most elite lifters utilize this bar path (up and back, then straight up), whereas most novice lifters drive the bar straight up initially, then up and back to lock out." .

ex:evidence_725534922184174758 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.492"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "frontiersin_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "A greater shoulder flexion moment could create higher demands on the proximal prime movers, while the narrow grip width could create higher demands on the distal prime movers; however, the only difference in muscle activity between the three grip widths was found in the medial triceps brachii, which was lower in the wide grip condition as compared with the other two." .

ex:evidence_7883411404938358189 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.455"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "muscleandmotion_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Incline Bench Press: In this exercise, a 30° inclination will produce greater activation of the pectoralis major’s upper portion." .

ex:evidence_8850144067794501424 a ex:EvidenceSentence ;
    ex:category "technique" ;
    ex:confidence "0.408"^^xsd:float ;
    ex:sourceFile "muscleandmotion_bench_press.html" ;
    rdfs:comment "Decline Bench Press: In this exercise, a 15° decline will produce greater activation of the lower pectoralis major. -" .

